  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 全履之哀詞
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 吾友全坦夫。字履之。惇信明敏。能文人也。仕至中軍錄事。先吾以仕而至予之已踐遺補。猶未遷秩。貞祐某年。佐元戎幕府。出征契丹之犯境者。方遷八品。遂隕命戰塲。予悲之。爲著詞云。古有儒將統三軍兮。制服戎虜如少兒兮。想夫子之非不爾兮。奈幕下之官卑。謀難專斷兮勇非所蓄。宜乎隕命之如斯。軍旅之未曾聞兮。仲尼有以著辭。胡吾子之習俎豆兮。遭玆鋒鏑之蹈危。援松指水有舊盟兮。淚橫隨兮哭以悲。已哉更不得覿兮。吾與誰兮論詩。豈無余子尙可同兮。獨子之詞兮簡而能披。
korean:
  title: 전리지 애사
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 나의 벗 전탄부(全坦夫)의 자는 이지(履之)인데, 돈신(惇信)하고, 명민(明敏)하며, 글 잘하는 사람이다. 벼슬은 중군녹사(中軍錄事)에 이르렀는데, 나보다 앞서서 벼슬하였으되, 내가 벌써 유보(遺補 습유ㆍ보궐의 병칭)에 이르렀음에도, 아직 천질(遷秩 승진)이 되지 못하였다. 정우(貞祐) 모년에 원수(元帥) 막부(幕府)의 보좌관이 되어 국경을 침범한 거란족을 나아가 치게 되어 바야흐로 8품직으로 옮겼고, 마침내는 전장에서 운명하였다. 나는 이를 슬퍼하여 그를 위하여 애사(哀詞)를 짓기를, “옛날 유장(儒將)이 있어 삼군(三軍)을 통솔할 때, 오랑캐를 제압함을 어린애 다루듯 함이여, 생각하니 그대도 그렇게 하지 않은 것은 아니겠지만, 막하의 관직이 낮아 어찌할꼬. 꾀를 전단하기 어려움이여, 용맹도 쌓은 것이 아니니 운명(隕命)이 이와 같은 것도 옳다 하겠네. 군사에 관한 일은 아직 듣지 못하였다고 공자께서 말씀하신 적도 있지 않은가. 그대는 선비의 예절을 배워 이 칼날과 같이 위험한 것을 밟아 죽음을 만날 줄을 어찌 알았겠는가. 소나무를 잡아당기고 물을 가리키는 옛 맹약이 있었음이여, 눈물이 비껴 흘러 울면서 슬퍼하네. 이미, 다시 만날 수 없게 되었으니, 나는 누구와 더불어 시를 논하겠는가. 어찌, 나와 자네의 취미가 같음이 없으랴마는, 유독 자네의 사(詞)는 간략하고도 툭 트였었네.” 하였다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1190_010_0030&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Elegy for Jeon Ryuji
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My friend Jeon Tanbu, whose courtesy name was Ryuji, was a man of profound integrity and keen intellect, skilled in letters and learning. He rose to the post of Military Recorder, advancing before me in service, yet even as I reached the rank of Supplementary Official, he had not yet received promotion. In the year of Zhenyou, he became adjutant to the Commander's staff, and marching forth against the Khitan invaders at our borders, he was finally advanced to the eighth rank—only to fall upon the battlefield. This sorrow moved me to compose this elegy for him:

    *In ancient times, the learned general commanded the three armies,*
    *Subduing the barbarians as one would tame a child.*
    *I think your talents were no lesser than theirs,*
    *Yet your station in the general's tent was humble and low.*
    *How could strategy flourish or valor find its flowering?*
    *Thus it was fitting that fate fell upon you as it did.*
    *Even Confucius spoke of the sage's distance from military affairs—*
    *How could you, schooled in ritual and refinement,*
    *Have foreseen that spears and arrows would be your path?*
    *We pledged our friendship by grasping pine and pointing to the stream,*
    *Yet now my tears flow as I weep in bitter sorrow.*
    *Gone now—I shall not see you again,*
    *With whom shall I discourse upon the poets' art?*
    *Others may share my tastes and temperament,*
    *Yet it was your words alone—spare and luminous—*
    *That opened my understanding.*
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three armies' (三軍) refers to the complete military forces of a kingdom.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Confucius concerns the Master's statement that the sage keeps distance from military matters, emphasizing the tragedy of a refined scholar forced into warfare.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of 'grasping pine and pointing to the stream' evokes an ancient Chinese tale of sworn friendship and covenant between companions.
